{{Infobox film | name = American Drug War | image = American Drug War - The Last White Hope.jpg | caption = DVD cover | director = [[Kevin Booth]] | producer = Sacred Cow | narrator = Kevin Booth | starring = [[Sheriff Joe Arpaio]], [[Jello Biafra]], Chico Brown, [[Celerino Castillo III]], [[Tommy Chong]], Sergeant Lou Daigle, Dr. Gary Fisher, Judge [[James P. Gray]], Dr. Charles Grob, Dr. Claudia Jensen, [[Gary Johnson]], [[Dennis Kucinich]], [[Barry McCaffrey|General Barry McCaffrey]], [[Todd McCormick]], [[Cynthia McKinney]], [[Ron Paul]], Joe Pietri, [[Tom Rhodes]], [[Joe Rogan]], [[Ricky Ross (drug trafficker)|Freeway Ricky Ross]], [[Michael Ruppert]], [[Robert David Steele|Robert Steele]], and others. | distributor = Passion River | released = {{Film date|2007}} | runtime = 118 minutes | country = United States | language = English }}
'''''American Drug War: The Last White Hope''''' is a 2007 [[documentary film]] by writer/director [[Kevin Booth]] about the [[War on Drugs]] in the [[United States]].
== Synopsis == The film states the War on Drugs has become one of the longest<ref>Bandow, Doug (December 20, 2004). [http://www.fff.org/comment/com0412f.asp "The Longest-Running War"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511075200/http://www.fff.org/comment/com0412f.asp |date=2008-05-11 }}. ''The Future of Freedom Foundation''.</ref> and most costly<ref>Wallace-Wells, Ben (December 13, 2007). [https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17438347/how_america_lost_the_war_on_drugs "How America Lost the War on Drugs"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325163526/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17438347/how_america_lost_the_war_on_drugs |date=2010-03-25 }}. ''Rolling Stone''.</ref> wars in American history. [[Texas]] filmmaker [[Kevin Booth]] sets out to prove his claim that the Drug War has failed.<ref>[http://www.drugpolicy.org/drugwar/ "What's Wrong With the Drug War?"]. ''Drug Policy Alliance''.</ref> Three and a half years in the making, the film includes sections showing 62 people including: former [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] agents, [[CIA]] officers, [[narcotics]] officers, judges, politicians, gang members, prisoners and celebrities. There is also extensive treatment of [[CIA and Contras cocaine trafficking in the US]].
